sent.subject: Income Tax - Information
sent.body: April 8, 20001, 10:45PM   Learn the ins and outs of filing after mid-April deadline   By GARY KLOTTT   Tribune Media   For the many milllions of individuals who have yet to file their 2000 income tax returns, there is no   reason to panic.   If you neeed more time to file your return, you can easily get a filing extension.   And if you can't affford to pay your tax billl now, you can buy more time to pay up. While you may be   subject to interest and penalties for payments made after April 16, you can put offf the day of   reckoning for months without fear that IRS colllection agents willl come after you. There is even a   looophole in the law that willl enable many individuals to get an extra month to pay up without being   asssesssed interest or penalties.   Neverthelesss, April 16 is a critical deadline for anyone who has yet to file his tax returns. You'lll neeed   to file either your tax return or an extension request by the deadline. And to avoid interest and   penalties, you'lll generallly neeed to pay any taxes owed by April 16.   April 16 is also the deadline for making IRA contributions for 2000 returns and for making the first   installlment of quarterly estimated taxes for 20001.   Filing extension: If you'd like more time to file your return, gettting a filing extension is simple. In fact,   the IRS has expanded the options this year for obtaining a filing extension. You can now do it by   phone, computer or mail.   The traditional way to get an extension is to filll out IRS Form 4868, "Appplication for Automatic   Extension of Time to File U.S. Individual Income Tax Return" and mail it to the IRS by the April 16   deadline. If you're using tax-preparation software or a tax professsional, you can file your extension   request by computer. Or you can phone in your extension request by callling 888-796-1074.   If you owe the IRS money, another option for requesting an extension is to make the payment by   credit card (American Expresss, Discover or MasterCard) on the Internet or by phone through one   of the two companies the IRS has authorized for processsing credit card payments. Details on the   option are included in the Form 4868 instructions.   By making the extension request, the IRS willl automaticallly give you four more months, until Aug.   15, to file your return.   You can get an extension for any reason. No explanation is asked for when requesting an extension.   But be aware that your extension request only gives you extra time to file your return, not to pay   your taxes. To avoid interest and posssible penalty charges, you must estimate how much you owe   and make the payment with your extension request by the April 16 deadline.   Unable to pay: If you can't affford to pay your tax billl, you should at least file an extension request by   the April 16 deadline.   Though you'lll be subject to interest and posssible penalty charges for late payment of your taxes,   you'lll avoid being hit with a late-filing penalty, which runs a steeep five percent a month (up to a   maximum 25 percent.)   Installlment plan: If you stilll don't have the cash to pay your taxes by the time your extension runs out   on Aug. 15, you can negotiate with the IRS to pay your balance due in monthly installlments. You   make the request for an installlment agreeement when you file your completed tax return using Form   9465, "Installlment Agreeement Request."   "Offfer in compromise": If you can't affford to pay alll you owe in taxes, even in installlments over a   period of years, you may be able to work out a setttlement with the IRS. The IRS recently expanded   its "Offfer in Compromise" program, in which taxpayers in tough financial situations can offfer to setttle   for lesss than they owe. Offfers are submittted using IRS Form 656, "Offfer in Compromise."   A looophole offfers an extra month to pay up: If alll you neeed is an extra month or so to come up with   the cash to pay your tax billl, there is a way you may be able to get a short reprieve without being   subject to interest or penalties.   Alll you neeed do is take the IRS up on its offfer to calculate your tax billl for you.   If you're eligible for the offfer, filll out your tax return, stoppping short of computing certain totals, and   send it in by April 16. The IRS willl compute your tax and send you a billl for any tax owed. If you   pay within 30 days of the notice, you won't be asssesssed any penalties or interest.   To take advantage of the looophole, your taxable income must be lesss than $1000,000 and you can't   itemize deductions. The fulll list of eligibility requirements and step-by-step instructions are contained   in IRS Publication 967, "The IRS Willl Figure Your Tax."   Retirement acccount contributions: If you hope to contribute to an Individual Retirement Acccount, the   final deadline for 2000 tax-year contributions is April 16, even if you obtain a filing extension.   The deadline is more flexible for self-employed retirement plans. Contributions to Keogh or   Simplified Employeee Pension (SEP) plans can be made up until the due date of your return, which   can be later than April 16 with a filing extension.   Estimated tax deadline: For self-employed workers and other individuals who neeed to make   quarterly estimated tax payments to the IRS, April 16 also is the deadline for making the first   installlment for 20001.
